# Global workshop defaults (committed). Sourced first by the bin/ scripts, then
# .workshoprc.local (per-machine, gitignored), then any per-slice .workshoprc — each layer
# overrides the previous. Keep machine-specific values (launcher, content dir, editor) in
# .workshoprc.local, not here.
#
# Every default below is written as "${VAR:-default}" (or "${VAR-default}" where an explicit
# empty value is meaningful) so an exported env var or a one-off `WORKSHOP_X=y bin/workshop`
# wins, while the later-sourced files still override unconditionally.

# Active pairing mode. See PAIRING_PROTOCOL.md for definitions.
#   navigator | coach | ping-pong | constraint | true-pair
WORKSHOP_MODE="${WORKSHOP_MODE:-navigator}"

# Where bin/workshop hands off to arrange your workspace. Launchers live in bin/launchers/.
#   manual  print the commands to run by hand — works in ANY editor, no deps (default)
#   tmux    nvim + watcher + AI in a 3-pane tmux session
#   vscode  open the folder(s) in VS Code and wire up the watch task
#   cursor  same, using the `cursor` binary
#   emacs   open the folder(s) in Emacs; print the watch + pair commands
# Set your preference per-machine in .workshoprc.local (it's gitignored), not here.
# Conditional so an exported env var or a one-off `WORKSHOP_LAUNCHER=tmux bin/workshop` wins;
# .workshoprc.local and per-slice .workshoprc (sourced later) still override.
WORKSHOP_LAUNCHER="${WORKSHOP_LAUNCHER:-manual}"

# Where practice content (missions, notes) lives. Defaults to the framework root, which is
# correct when you keep everything in one checkout. Point it at a separate personal repo to
# keep your content out of a shared framework clone. Export it (in .workshoprc.local or your
# shell profile) so the Ruby tools (bin/note) see it too.
#   export WORKSHOP_CONTENT_DIR="$HOME/src/workshop-personal"
WORKSHOP_CONTENT_DIR="${WORKSHOP_CONTENT_DIR:-}"

# Test command invoked by the watcher on file change.
# Defaults to Rails' bin/rspec stub (faster than bundle exec; uses bootsnap).
# Override to `bundle exec rspec` for plain Ruby projects, or to anything else.
WORKSHOP_TEST_CMD="${WORKSHOP_TEST_CMD:-bin/rspec}"

# Directories to watch (space-separated). The watcher recurses for *.rb and *.ru.
WORKSHOP_WATCH_GLOB="${WORKSHOP_WATCH_GLOB:-lib spec config app}"

# Tmux layout used by the tmux launcher (bin/launchers/tmux). Only 'default' is implemented
# (editor left, watcher bottom-left, AI + term windows).
WORKSHOP_TMUX_LAYOUT="${WORKSHOP_TMUX_LAYOUT:-default}"

# Project type, used by bin/new-slice if it needs to scaffold.
# Templates live in templates/<type>/. Unset = no scaffolding.
WORKSHOP_PROJECT_TYPE="${WORKSHOP_PROJECT_TYPE-}"

# External-target mission: absolute path to the repo where code lands (set per-slice).
# When set, the launcher opens the editor + term on that repo and gives a claude AI pane
# --add-dir to it, while the watcher + AI keep the slice as cwd. Empty = self-contained
# kata (everything stays in the slice). Use $HOME, never a hardcoded home, so the same
# config works across machines. See PAIRING_PROTOCOL.md.
WORKSHOP_TARGET_REPO="${WORKSHOP_TARGET_REPO-}"

# github-project shape: the unit of work lives in GitHub Issues + a Projects v2 board.
# Epic issue ↔ mission, Task issue ↔ slice. bin/issue reads these (flags > env > the
# mission's MISSION.md fields). Empty = not a github-project mission. See
# GITHUB_PROJECT_SHAPE.md.
#   WORKSHOP_GH_REPO     owner/name slug, e.g. your-org/your-repo
#   WORKSHOP_GH_PROJECT  Projects v2 number, e.g. 4
#   WORKSHOP_GH_ISSUE    the Task issue this slice implements (set per-slice)
WORKSHOP_GH_REPO="${WORKSHOP_GH_REPO-}"
WORKSHOP_GH_PROJECT="${WORKSHOP_GH_PROJECT-}"

# TUI editor command for the tmux launcher's 'code' pane. Honors your $EDITOR; empty when
# $EDITOR is unset, which leaves a plain shell (handy when you edit on the host in a GUI
# editor and don't want a TUI editor seized into a pane). Set it explicitly in
# .workshoprc.local (e.g. WORKSHOP_EDITOR="nvim .") to override. Ignored by the GUI
# launchers (vscode/cursor/emacs), which open their own editor. The outer ${VAR-...} keeps
# an env override (including an explicit empty value) ahead of the $EDITOR-derived default.
WORKSHOP_EDITOR="${WORKSHOP_EDITOR-${EDITOR:+$EDITOR .}}"

# Command for the 'term' window. Empty = plain shell. For an external-target mission
# whose target runs in Docker, set this per-slice to log into the container, e.g.
# WORKSHOP_TERM_CMD="cd \$HOME/src/my-target-repo && make login".
WORKSHOP_TERM_CMD="${WORKSHOP_TERM_CMD-}"

# AI pair partner command, launched in the right column on boot.
# Set empty to leave the pane idle (e.g. WORKSHOP_AI_CMD="").
WORKSHOP_AI_CMD="${WORKSHOP_AI_CMD-claude}"
